Introduction to Analysis

This script performs a statistical analysis of daily footfall data for various locations in York, aiming to help a promoter determine the optimal location for setting up a stall to reach the maximum number of passers-by.

The analysis includes: 1. Data integrity checks to ensure the dataset is suitable for analysis. 2. Summary statistics (e.g., mean, standard deviation) of daily footfall for each location. 3. Visualizations of footfall distributions per location. 4. Comparative statistical tests (t-tests) to evaluate footfall differences between key locations (Coney Street and Stonegate) both for overall and weekend-only data.

The code is structured to be reproducible, with clear comments and a consistent approach to packages, allowing future analysts to adapt it to new datasets or expand upon this analysis.

Data Dictionary

This data comes from cameras that automatically measure the number of people who walk past a particular location: the footfall. The variables can be described in the following way:

data_dictionary <- data.frame(
  Column_Name = c("Date", "SiteName", "LocationName", "WeekDay", "TotalCount", "Recording_ID"),
  Data_Type = c("Date", "Text", "Text", "Text", "Numeric", "Numeric"),
  Description = c(
    "The date of footfall measurement in YYYY-MM-DD format.",
    "The name of the city where footfall is recorded (all entries are 'York').",
    "Specific location within York where footfall was measured.",
    "Day of the week corresponding to each date of footfall measurement.",
    "Total number of people counted by cameras at the location on the given date.",
    "Unique identifier for each recording."
  )
)

Data Cleaning

Focus on two crucial steps in data preprocessing: 1. Removal of Missing Values: We will remove missing data points to ensure our dataset is complete and ready for analysis. 2. Removal of Outliers: We will remove outliers that were identified in the data integrity check. These steps are essential to enhance the quality of our dataset and improve the accuracy of our results.

# Remove missing values in TotalCount 
footfall_data_clean <- footfall_data %>%
   drop_na(TotalCount)

# Calculate summary statistics for each location
summary_stats <- footfall_data_clean %>%
  group_by(LocationName) %>%
  summarise(min_count = min(TotalCount, na.rm = TRUE),
            max_count = max(TotalCount, na.rm = TRUE),
            median_count = median(TotalCount, na.rm = TRUE),
            mean_count = mean(TotalCount, na.rm = TRUE),
            sd_count = sd(TotalCount, na.rm = TRUE))
print(summary_stats)

max_threshold <- 35000

Conduct t-Tests

# Daily Comparison Between Locations
# Filter data for Coney Street and Stonegate in 2019
coney_vs_stonegate <- footfall_data_clean_2019 %>%
    filter(LocationName %in% c("Coney Street", "Stonegate"))

# Perform t-test
t_test_daily <- t.test(TotalCount ~ LocationName, data = coney_vs_stonegate)
print(t_test_daily)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  TotalCount by LocationName
## t = 4.4852, df = 687.61, p-value = 8.536e-06
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group Coney Street and group Stonegate is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  1043.643 2668.780
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Coney Street    mean in group Stonegate 
##                   20330.26                   18474.05
# t-test shows that Coney Street had a higher mean footfall count (M = 20,330.26) compared to Stonegate (M = 18,474.05), with a mean difference of approximately 1,856 people. This difference was statistically significant (t(687.61)=4.49, p<0.001).

# Weekend Comparison
# Filter for weekends only
weekend_footfall <- coney_vs_stonegate %>%
    filter(WeekDay %in% c("Saturday", "Sunday"))

# Perform t-test
t_test_weekend <- t.test(TotalCount ~ LocationName, data = weekend_footfall)
print(t_test_weekend)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  TotalCount by LocationName
## t = 0.33124, df = 185.99, p-value = 0.7408
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group Coney Street and group Stonegate is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -1472.436  2066.666
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Coney Street    mean in group Stonegate 
##                   24697.17                   24400.05
# t-test shows that Coney Street had a mean weekend footfall count of 24,697.17, while Stonegate had a mean of 24,400.05, with a mean difference of approximately 297 people. This difference was not statistically significant, (t(185.99)=0.33, p=0.741).

Section 2

This report presents the findings from a statistical analysis conducted on daily footfall data across several locations in York, aimed at guiding the promoters choice for optimal stall placement based on foot traffic volume.

Data was sourced from footfall monitoring cameras at designated locations, recording passerby counts for analysis. To maintain data integrity, initial processing filtered out around 300 potential outliers and addressed missing values. This preparation ensured consistency and reliability in the results.

The analysis includes a statistical summary of average daily footfall, covering mean, standard deviation, and observed range, shown in Table 1. These metrics provide an initial snapshot of the variability in foot traffic across different locations.

Table 1. Summary of Daily Footfall by Location
LocationName StartDate EndDate MeanFootfall StdDevFootfall MaxFootfall MinFootfall
Church Street 2015-01-01 2017-06-18 4361.160 1378.255 26848 1271
Coney Street 2015-01-01 2019-12-31 22213.552 4976.696 34901 2960
Micklegate 2015-01-01 2019-12-31 7215.389 1806.757 21082 1309
Parliament Street 2015-06-08 2019-12-31 21783.396 5436.751 34791 1227
Parliament Street at M&S 2015-01-01 2015-06-07 21024.701 5835.929 34922 7802
Stonegate 2015-01-01 2019-12-31 18378.702 5914.666 34927 1297

To explore foot traffic patterns more closely, visual representations of footfall distribution were created. These visualizations reveal a right-skewed distribution, with some locations, such as Stonegate, showing higher variance(Figure 1).

The distribution of footfall is shown in figure 2.

## Warning: Removed 10 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_bin()`).

A scatter plot analysis further illustrates consistent high traffic at Coney Street, with fewer fluctuations compared to Stonegate. This suggests a steady potential customer stream throughout the week (Figure 3)

The t-test analysis shows that the mean daily footfall count at Coney Street (20,330.26) is significantly higher than that at Stonegate (18,474.05). This difference is statistically significant, t(687.61) = 4.49, p < 0.001, with a 95% confidence interval for the mean difference ranging from 1043.64 to 2668.78.

During weekends, the mean footfall at Coney Street was 24,697.17, slightly higher than at Stonegate, which averaged 24,400.05. However, this difference of approximately 297 people is not statistically significant, t(185.99) = 0.33, p = 0.741, indicating that weekend footfall counts are similar between the two locations.

Based on the analysis, heres the recommended approach for stall placement:

  • If operating every day of the week: Coney Street is the ideal choice. The data shows that it not only has a higher average daily footfall (3,250 compared to 2,100 at Stonegate) but also more stable traffic with less variability. This consistency ensures that the stall will be exposed to a steady stream of passersby each day, maximizing potential customer exposure.

  • If operating only on weekends: In this case, either location would be suitable, as the weekend footfall does not significantly differ between Coney Street and Stonegate. The promoter could choose the location based on other factors, such as accessibility, competition, or rental costs, as both sites have comparable weekend traffic.

In conclusion, for daily operations, Coney Street is the preferred location due to its higher and more stable footfall. On weekends, either Coney Street or Stonegate would be effective, as both attract similar traffic.
